1. Dataset Selection

The data set used in this project describes the performance evaluation of cars produced by Japanese, American, and European manufacturers. The entire dataset is obtained from UCI database. According to the website, we can learn that the data set is taken from the StatLib library maintained by Carnegie Mellon University. This data set was used at the 1983 American Statistical Association Exposition. This dataset is often used for example and model-based learning. Therefore, this data set is very friendly to beginners due to its simple structure. Therefore, this project will combine the knowledge learned to mine the information contained in this data set.

In addition, from the information given on the website, the data set contains nine features. The names, descriptions and variable types of these nine features (variables) are shown in the table below. From the information in the table, we can find that these nine variables include five continuous variables, three integer variables and one discrete variable. Although the variable origin is an integer value, it is actually a discrete variable. In addition, the variable car name can be understood as the ID of the vehicle. It is pointless to study this variable.

In data analysis, outliers refer to extreme values that are significantly different from other observed values in the data set. They can be due to measurement error, data entry errors, sample bias, or real extreme situations. Outliers can have an impact on the descriptive statistics of your data, such as mean and standard deviation. For continuous variables, we generally identify them based on box plots and standard deviations. Both methods are based on the basis of the normal distribution. Here, I first observe the histogram of these 5 continuous variables. From the results of the histogram, it can be found that the variables displacement and horsepower exhibit a severely right-skewed distribution. In other words, there are some extremely large records for these two variables that can easily be identified as outliers.

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
hist(df$mpg, col = 'seagreen',  main = 'mpg', xlab = '')
hist(df$displacement, col = 'seagreen', main = 'displacement', xlab = '')
hist(df$horsepower, col = 'seagreen',   main = 'horsepower', xlab = '')
hist(df$weight, col = 'seagreen',  main = 'weight', xlab = '')
hist(df$acceleration, col = 'seagreen',  main = 'acceleration', xlab = '')

Here, I take the logarithm of these two variables to improve their volatility. It can be found from the histogram that the distribution of the logarithmic data is close to a symmetrical bell-shaped distribution. This shows that taking the logarithm can help reduce the skewness of the data, making the data easier to compare.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(log(df$displacement), main = 'log(displacement)', xlab = '', col = 'seagreen')
hist(log(df$horsepower), main = 'log(horsepower)', xlab = '', col = 'seagreen')

Boxplots can show the distribution of data and outliers. Outliers are typically defined as data points that fall outside the “whiskers” of a boxplot. Outliers in continuous variables can be initially identified by examining outliers in boxplots. It can be found from the figure that the variables acceleration have outliers.

par(mfrow = c(2, 3))
boxplot(df$mpg, col = 'seagreen', pch = 16, horizontal = T, main = 'mpg')

boxplot(df$weight, col = 'seagreen', pch = 16, horizontal = T, main = 'weight')
boxplot(df$acceleration, col = 'seagreen', pch = 16, horizontal = T, main = 'acceleration')

The standard deviation-based method means that by calculating the mean and standard deviation of the data, data points that are far away from the mean can be identified. Generally speaking, observations outside the range of more than 3 times the standard deviation are considered outliers. Here, I wrote a function to identify possible outliers in five continuous variables. It can be found from the results that there are 2 outliers in the variable acceleration.

get_outliers <- function(x){
  x <- x[x < (mean(x) - 3*sd(x))|x > (mean(x) + 3*sd(x))]
  if(length(x) == 0){
    print('No outliers')
  }else{
    return(x)
  }
}

get_outliers(df$mpg)
## [1] "No outliers"
get_outliers(log(df$displacement))
## [1] "No outliers"
get_outliers(log(df$horsepower))
## [1] "No outliers"
get_outliers(df$weight)
## [1] "No outliers"
get_outliers(df$acceleration)
## [1] 24.8 24.6

Based on the above analysis, I will delete the two records with values 24.8 and 24.6 in the variable acceleration variable, because both methods consider these two values to be outliers.

df <- df[df$acceleration  < 24.6, ]

All five types of cylinder counts are common, so I don’t think there are outliers on this variable. The variable origin indicates the origin of the car, and the data set contains three different origins. Therefore, I don’t think the variable origin has an outlier. Other variables are unimportant and the information they contain has no impact on the quality of the data set. Therefore, this item will not be discussed.

In addition, we know from the previous analysis that the variables horsepower and displacement show a severely right-skewed distribution, and I need to take the logarithm of it to reduce the skewness of the data.

library(dplyr)
df <- mutate(df,
             origin = factor(origin, levels = 1:3, labels = c('USA', 'Europe', 'Japan')),
             horsepower = log(horsepower),
             displacement = log(displacement))
colnames(df)[3:4] <- c('log(displacement)', 'log(horsepower)')

4. Descriptive Analysis

In this module, the first question that interests me is what are the differences in performance between cars from different origins. Here, I use box plots and bar charts to show the performance of cars from different origins. Figure ‘I’ in the figure below depicts the number of miles traveled by cars from different origins when supplied with the same gasoline. It can be found from the figure that cars made in Japan are the most fuel-efficient, followed by cars made in Europe. Figure ‘II’ shows the difference in engine displacement. The figure shows that engines produced in the United States generally have larger displacements, while the engine displacements of cars produced in Japan and those produced in Europe are similar. Figures ‘III’ and ‘IV’ respectively represent the differences in horsepower and weight of cars from different origins. These two characteristics behave in the same way as the engine displacement. Figure V shows the difference in the acceleration capabilities of cars. From the figure, it can be found that cars made in the United States have relatively strong acceleration capabilities. In addition, in terms of the number of cylinders in cars, most cars made in the United States have more than 5 cylinders, while most cars made in Japan have less than 5 cylinders, and cars made in Europe are in the middle. Generally speaking, cars made in Japan are lighter and more fuel-efficient, but have less horsepower, while cars made in the United States are bulky, more fuel-efficient, but have strong horsepower.

In this project, the second question I am interested in is whether we can reduce the dimensionality of these indicator information that describes the car, so that only two or three indicators can be used to describe the performance of the car. Here, I calculated the correlation for each variable. A visualization of the correlation is shown below. From the results, it can be found that the variables cylinders, displacement, horsepower and weight have a strong positive correlation with each other. These four variables all show a strong negative correlation with the variable mpg, but a weak positive correlation with the variable acceleration. This implies that we can refine the variables cylinders, displacement, horsepower and weight into a new variable, such as a car’s powertrain. Based on this basis, we can use the variables mpg and acceleration to replace the original data set to describe the performance of the car.

library('corrr')
library("ggcorrplot")
library("FactoMineR")
library("devtools")
library("factoextra")

corr_matrix <- cor(df[,-7])
ggcorrplot(corr_matrix)

Next, I perform dimensionality reduction analysis using principal components. From the results of principal component analysis, it can be found that the first two principal components can explain 90% of the fluctuations in the original data. Then, I visualized the loading matrix from the principal component analysis. It can be found from the figure that the first principal component can well explain the variables weight, displacement, cylinders, horsepower and mpg, while the second principal component mainly explains the variable acdeleration . This implies that the first principal component is mainly related to the power system of the car. The more powerful the car, the higher the fuel consumption. The second principal component is related to acceleration. In addition, I also drew a scatter plot of different cars based on principal component scores. From the figure, we can find that cars made in the United States have lower first principal component scores, while cars made in Europe and Japan have higher scores. First principal component score. But their differences in the second principal component scores are not significant.

The description of a car can only focus on two aspects. One is the car’s power system. Powerful cars tend to consume more fuel. The other is the car’s acceleration performance.
